The only real way to solve this is to ensure that the `width` of the container is constrained to be (roughly) twice the length of the text.

For example, the following text is roughly 630 pixels long, so setting a `width` of `315px` in addition to `word-wrap: break-word` causes the text to be of equal length on both lines:

&lt;!-- begin snippet: js hide: false console: true babel: false --&gt;

&lt;!-- language: lang-css --&gt;

    .example {
      width: 315px;
      word-wrap: break-word;
    }

&lt;!-- language: lang-html --&gt;

    &lt;div class=&quot;example&quot;&gt;AVeryVeryVeryVeryLongUrl/SomeFolder/SomeSubFolder/SomePage.htmlisthebestfileextension&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;!-- end snippet --&gt;

Note that with JavaScript&#39;s [`.offsetWidth`][1] you can calculate the existing width and set the new width automatically, though I don&#39;t *believe* this is possibly with a combination of [`calc()`][2] and [`width: fit-width`][3] in pure CSS.

&lt;!-- begin snippet: js hide: false console: true babel: false --&gt;

&lt;!-- language: lang-js --&gt;

    var example = document.getElementsByClassName(&#39;example&#39;)[0];
    example.style.width = example.offsetWidth / 2 - 8 + &quot;px&quot;;
    // Half the current width, also accounting for the 8px of margin

&lt;!-- language: lang-css --&gt;

    .example {
      word-wrap: break-word;
    }

&lt;!-- language: lang-html --&gt;

    &lt;div class=&quot;example&quot;&gt;AVeryVeryVeryVeryLongUrl/SomeFolder/SomeSubFolder/SomePage.htmlisthebestfileextension&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;!-- end snippet --&gt;


  [1]: https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/API/HTMLElement/offsetWidth
  [2]: https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/CSS/calc
  [3]: https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/CSS/width

